mSDcWvnNlGqtXk4vihe0=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Mockito integration**\\n\\nI’m considering whether to add the Mockito dependency and if it has native support. Using dynamic proxies or bytecode seems unlikely to work, so perhaps I could create a subclass of MappedField. However, the only constructors are package-private, which complicates things since I can’t access it outside the package. I might evaluate using public API to create MappedField while avoiding cglib, as it could lead to compatibility issues. There’s also the option of setting a static field via reflection, but I know that’s generally not recommended unless necessary.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Addressing LazyFeatureDependencies**\\n\\nI’m looking at LazyFeatureDependencies and need to ensure its `fulFilled` status is set to non-null false without loading cglib. Since there isn’t a public API to achieve this, I’m wondering about adding a JVM argument, but I'm uncertain if that would resolve Mapper construction issues due to cglib's potential dynamic class generation problems. I could consider removing MappedField tests, but I need to ensure line 122 and 196 are covered. It might be feasible to adjust how I create lists and maps, potentially routing around the problematic lines while fixing the failing tests.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering reflection for LazyFeatureDependencies**\\n\\nI’m really weighing the idea of using minimal reflection to set `LazyFeatureDependencies.fulFilled` to false before Mapper construction. But would that work in a native environment? In native, I think setting a private static field via reflection would require metadata for LazyFeatureDependencies to be properly accessed. Since user code filters in org.mongodb.morphia, I need to consider how the agent would generate that. I’m curious if direct reflection from the test on the Morphia class will be tracked in any way.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating library usage**\\n\\nI'm considering how to handle the integration of cglib and Morphia. If I exclude cglib, Morphia’s lazy features won't work, but the DefaultCreator class might still be acceptable. I wonder if in reachability metadata testing, I should check the library normally. I think I might not want to broaden my approach. An alternative could be to add the JVM argument --add-opens just for tests. However, I’m curious about how this will affect native tests on the JVM.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_gnzwMD0A2JLsQX3jiPvRT81T|fc_06ebc20508d9f1a8016a0261ae3f04819ea3c950933d6a8c22", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg \"cglib|proxytoys\" -n ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.mongodb.morphia/morphia/1.3.2 ~/.m2/repository/org/mongodb/morphia/morphia/1.3.2 2>/dev/null || true"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2090, "output": 1251, "cacheRead": 30720, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 34061, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778540955044, "responseId": "resp_06ebc20508d9f1a8016a02619b8650819ea403b6aaff1c87ad"}}
