[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating Mockito integration**\n\nI’m considering whether to add the Mockito dependency and if it has native support. Using dynamic proxies or bytecode seems unlikely to work, so perhaps I could create a subclass of MappedField. However, the only constructors are package-private, which complicates things since I can’t access it outside the package. I might evaluate using public API to create MappedField while avoiding cglib, as it could lead to compatibility issues. There’s also the option of setting a static field via reflection, but I know that’s generally not recommended unless necessary.\n\n**Addressing LazyFeatureDependencies**\n\nI’m looking at LazyFeatureDependencies and need to ensure its `fulFilled` status is set to non-null false without loading cglib. Since there isn’t a public API to achieve this, I’m wondering about adding a JVM argument, but I'm uncertain if that would resolve Mapper construction issues due to cglib's potential dynamic class generation problems. I could consider removing MappedField tests, but I need to ensure line 122 and 196 are covered. It might be feasible to adjust how I create lists and maps, potentially routing around the problematic lines while fixing the failing tests.\n\n**Considering reflection for LazyFeatureDependencies**\n\nI’m really weighing the idea of using minimal reflection to set `LazyFeatureDependencies.fulFilled` to false before Mapper construction. But would that work in a native environment? In native, I think setting a private static field via reflection would require metadata for LazyFeatureDependencies to be properly accessed. Since user code filters in org.mongodb.morphia, I need to consider how the agent would generate that. I’m curious if direct reflection from the test on the Morphia class will be tracked in any way.\n\n**Evaluating library usage**\n\nI'm considering how to handle the integration of cglib and Morphia. If I exclude cglib, Morphia’s lazy features won't work, but the DefaultCreator class might still be acceptable. I wonder if in reachability metadata testing, I should check the library normally. I think I might not want to broaden my approach. An alternative could be to add the JVM argument --add-opens just for tests. However, I’m curious about how this will affect native tests on the JVM.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_06ebc20508d9f1a8016a02619c4870819e993d41d2beb13050\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqAmGutCMR3URX918OsxGIA5RHcfMjZx9bSPx5RanBKDiosXK08h75kGRlCaO7ZeLN5crzdN8uCizmXrYJtLsmYykH4yZb-V2I3zh36ZxhXVV_FO8IwZcKv-kFlKeNigXBtifQHU6b3TohJsHpDpbtEUASEHv66Ke4G6kWqnWqNEKavUGiAYslhymOgrk_VDAeDf-el9XdGM9LT1TYTQrlO1B1wzjR9CYfwaJLBJCzn-G_3ky4RM0Q6489L0mpsrp8tMvn46QmztoBidmycoFK9iJIZoCPQRM74ZHEcJuHARoYFOytsMtPenhXbrN3bMa5y5jN5U_KbCiUjsJmDpt86XrqSOtFHKHaAQuxB6lJA8_Nc0MsvhTSTglcZlRWdMtwfm-Z6KJjEEbYC9VOWml2uvacF4dXk6xDa4BdlWxRmwaqzynaGe3T6f3wul0aRtOx_JeeHXbrlDz0WXuZVZ14AXgtIZsTg0lm4Af1DqeyOvhvJ5lf8K4WpaIbIuu3xAb7-ZFYXPa0zqLLbWJ84r4_vjyt09n0MnA2DspFVBdsxU4D9OGy1NbbC46CcHAIWFxT0cG8fjAeXAeFjehK3J72euemAcKRVTmmwy_EXB12GP2In4_Ps5TWUnsMuVbRtbmhEdYntvgr1Eoh7IZQJVAlBi3Ben0BzoPGPLgWIwYZxduUQthKKujJVve6e4BWCC4KTHNkiy5LEUduWAlN_zCbmKtkEi6nJwPRMBe8WvcGMa4iG9U-JfBqSRuhPTWyvUq9oSOESp1Q8bEKTJveIOZ7r-Z59v4XPK6w2o3snaUxFg3m9CcYmqRpVaA2TbTMrdOD3Dmz3nZuX6Y-E34agaFCL4-DrWp0hjdpdiieadw6u5k-9eWhU-XPvB8892oMrQLzaEAaoXbxj19x3svYeLCjv1STHybmOkpyVsanZtY0g1WIPKrY61fTELlq_dpXJFhHEsP7c65aZqJonRhDAZhkeM-GkJ0yDTrudqgujYGXi_b4Vh-G-JZGRPxTz_Mgv8LGwKwJBJ_pRkplo4gm4yYxfmtDmF5a4_3NDo1KH8sITR4r47Zn9NR16SZ6SqIuYI1VQDsOG7NHH-gHeWLDRj-MILhsmoNZYCpGX7QflcPsYauZK1ormwYPhR0lz3VNT_BZxD5GrrvtxCLEZJSNz_MAtct2U1JF4E4x8p0hXNxflxNT249KRlc2bHW58Yb_EYpXIBh_l6MZwcBxtevOvzCBVFANdasTV0OPJiMve5RKH0ZIEY1vpxCNguQK7v4HccVRPwi4DkuCNnR-nkYZmoU33mq4Y7AvcA-ciPttkk1A4EKhiXydsTL5ThQr_PNOk1650e3FnKKCCh6IEMmQfYZeZM8jF6tk-nd_gwOaCbcZ8yVfX3ipNuoBgzp9S5sXad193E5at2WFz-vFJAO-55n2E9mpLbUMma